@page "/blogs/using-linq-chunk-to-split-data"
@using LINQDemoComponents
@inherits BasePage

<Content FileName=@nameof(LINQChunk)>
    <ContentBody>
        <What>
            <p>
                In this article, let's learn about how to use <Highlight>Chunk</Highlight> in <Highlight>LINQ</Highlight> in .NET.
            </p>

            <p>
                <strong>Note:</strong> If you have not done so already, I recommend you read the article on
                <NavLink href="blogs/using-linq-distinct-to-select-unique-data" Match="NavLinkMatch.All">Using LINQ Distinct to Select Specific Data in Collections</NavLink>.
            </p>
        </What>

        <Why>
            <p>
                Splitting a large collection into fixed-size batches is a common need, especially for pagination, bulk API calls, or batch processing. Without
                <Highlight>Chunk()</Highlight>, you'd track an index and manually slice the list. <Highlight>Chunk()</Highlight> expresses this intent clearly and concisely
                with minimal code.
            </p>
        </Why>

        <How>
            <h4 id="chunk">Split collections into smaller collections using Chunk</h4>

            <p>
                Let's partition data into other format. We can split our (Larger) Collection into array of smaller collections using Chunk() method. This will give list of data array. What
                <Highlight>Chunk(n)</Highlight> does is that it takes first n items from collection and build an array with that items and put them into first item of our final list.
                Then it takes second n items from collection build an array and put it into second item of our final list forming collection of collections.
            </p>

            <CodeSnippet CssClass="language-csharp">
List&lt;Product&gt; products = GetProducts();

//Method Syntax
List&lt;Product[]&gt; partitionedProducts = products
                                      .Chunk(1)
                                      .ToList();
                    
//Query Syntax
List&lt;Product[]&gt; partitionedProducts = (from product in products select product)
                                      .Chunk(1)
                                      .ToList();
            </CodeSnippet>

            <DemoSnippet Title="LINQ Chunk Clause Demo">
                <p>
                    Let's try LINQ Chunk
                </p>

                <ul class="[ list-disc ] [ ml-4 ]">
                    <li>We have <Highlight>Product</Highlight> class with following properties - <Highlight>Id, Name, Color, Price, Size</Highlight></li>
                    <li>Enter the number of products you would like to list.</li>
                    <li>Click on Chunk Button</li>
                    <li>Click on reset to try other combination</li>
                </ul>

                <ChunkDemo></ChunkDemo>
            </DemoSnippet>
        </How>

        <Summary>
            <p>
                In this article we learn't how to split data within collection using <Highlight>Chunk</Highlight>. This can be used for pagination for small in-memory collections to
                improve user experience. All these can be used with any <Highlight>IEnumerable</Highlight> or <Highlight>IQueryable</Highlight> types.
            </p>
        </Summary>
    </ContentBody>
</Content>